A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
In recognition of a critical operational need for expanded response options, the FY 1996 National Defense Authorization Act established a Defense Non-Lethal Weapons
(NLW) Program. This strategic mandate vested the Commandant of the Marine Corps (CMC) with the centralized responsibility to serve as the program's Executive
Agent (EA).

 This program directly supports the National Defense Strategy (NDS) by developing non-lethal capabilities that give the Joint Force options in legally or politically
 constrained scenarios. These "intermediate force" options complement lethal firepower, particularly in highly dense, metropolitan based, complex environments
 where the distinction between combatant and non-combatant is paramount. By providing commanding officers with capabilities designed to preserve life and prevent
 unintended tragedy, these options demonstrate a profound commitment to humanitarian principles ? a core value that strengthens our alliances with NATO and other
 key partners.

 All research and development (R&D) investments are driven by the Joint Non-Lethal Weapons Integrated Product Team, a multi-service flag-level board that provides
 executive oversight for the Executive Agent (EA). This joint approach addresses capability gaps identified in Joint Requirements Oversight Council (JROC) approved
 documents, ensuring the most relevant technologies are provided to the warfighter while eliminating duplicative investment across the services.

 The Joint Intermediate Force Capabilities Office (JIFCO) (formally Joint Non-Lethal Weapons Directorate) is designated as a Research and Development (R&D)
 organization and was established by the EA to manage the day-to-day research and development activities of the JNLWP. Each Service is responsible for their
 procurement and operating support costs.




