$$, $$e29abea5b706a45bcaf73625814afc94fe722f173df80bcee617ac11f0601963$$, $${"A": "ef7e4d7d44a3b4c4e5c1d8bcef55b44368ce1bb171957b0139b3475f3f6d2951", "C": "d4fdf923ba776b98bda680220afe7660b2fb7f78e25f4cb026ad0b29031d9620", "D": "ee43f3d6721b1a121639c6f018bb7928dbaaecb141afa9e1bebfc63dda8b145d"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY27/Army/RDTE - Vol 1 - Budget Activity 3.pdf$$, 239, $$2026-05-10T04:04:16.617786+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$1206399SF$$, 2027, $$The Space Systems Integration Office (SSIO) is executing Space Systems Command (SSC) Enterprise Engineering & Integration (Project 664111) for Guardians across
Space Control, Global Mission Operations (GMO), and Space Access operational functions and Command and Control and Networks enterprise functions supporting
operational warfighting, operational commands, combat support, and combat service support units. As a result, the Service will improve battle management integrated
of all weapon systems; streamline capabilities development through institutional processes; and augment, supplement, and/or integrate Allies, partners, and commercial
space to USSF units.

 The primary mission of SSIO is to orchestrate and integrate end-to-end capability delivery for warfighter operations across all Space Force Program Executive Officers
 (PEOs) and Portfolio Acquisition Executives (PAEs), Space Force Field Commands, Combatant Commands, and mission partners such as the Department of the Air
 Force Rapid Capabilities Office (AFRCO), the Missile Defense Agency (MDA), and the National Reconnaissance Office (NRO). SSIO is the only USSF office that looks
 throughout the fielded and programmed force to integrate kill chains across PEOs/PAEs and partners to deter, defeat, and dominate a dynamic red threat.

 In 2021, the Space Force established SSIO. In July 2024, the Assistant Secretary of the Air Force for Space Acquisition and Integration (ASAF)(SA&I) broadened
 SSIO's mission and designated SSIO as the organization responsible for integration across all Space Force PEO/PAE portfolios to include SSC, Space Development
 Agency (SDA), and the Space Rapid Capabilities Office (SpRCO). In April 2025, the ASAF(SA&I) appointed a Senior Advisor to the Service Acquisition Executive
 (SASAE), and, in response to a 2025 NDAA requirement, the Senior Advisor for Space Command, Control, and Integration (SASC2I). The SASAE is the USSF lead
 for System of Systems Engineering (SoSE) across the space acquisition enterprise and is responsible to drive engineering and assess all acquisition efforts under
 the authority of the ASAF(SA&I) portfolio and applicable mission partner organizations. This includes advising the Service Acquisition Executive (SAE) on matters of
 enforcement needed to enable and accelerate integrated enterprise capability delivery. The SASC2I is responsible for conducting oversight of all acquisition efforts
 within the authority of the ASAF(SA&I) with respect to developing, upgrading, deploying, and sustaining space command, control, and integration to meet the space
 command, control, and integration requirements of the combatant commands. SSIO executes the functions necessary to meet these responsibilities on behalf of the
 SASAE and SASC2I.

 SSIO advises the ASAF(SA&I) on strategy to inform PEO portfolios across all mission areas to meet warfighting needs. These efforts also provide systems engineering
 for the space component of the Command, Control, Communications, and Battle Management (C3BM) portfolio to deliver an integrated command and control
 architecture to support the joint fight. SSIO enterprise-level integration includes three lines of effort. The first is Enterprise Mission Integration and Analysis which
 supports a multitude of Space Force programs at all classification levels needed to close mission threads and kill chains and deliver war-winning capabilities. The

RDT&E Management Support
 second is Enterprise Technical Governance and Requirements management which delivers enterprise standards across cyber, crypto, spectrum, and digital ecosystem,
 matures enterprise enabling capabilities including supply chain risk management and space industrial base foreign influence mitigation and documents and enforces
 technical governance for space programs to a manage a cohesive warfighting technical baseline and ensure integration across the space enterprise. The third is Space
 Futures which defines the future operating environment, prioritizes science and technology initiatives, and supports wargaming required to refine operational concepts.

 This program falls within the Enterprise Management & Information Technology mission area. Enterprise Management provides the personnel and infrastructure
 required to manage USSF headquarters functions at the service and field command levels, including the Space Service Acquisition Executive for Space Systems
 and Programs, Office of the Assistant Secretary for Space Acquisition and Integration, the Office of the Chief of Space Operations (OCSO), the Space Staff, and
 Secretariat. Information Technology includes the IT infrastructure required for the USSF to acquire, sustain, and operate its assets. Space Force investment program
 interdependencies include:

 RDT&E Budget Line Items: Acq Workforce - Space & Missile Sys (1206392SF); Headquarters U.S. Space Force (1209398SF); Space & Missile Systems Center - MHA
 (1206398SF); Space Security and Defense Program (1206730SF); Space Warfighting Analysis (1203622SF); Service Wide Support (1201212SF); Commercial Services
 (1206771SF); and elements of Procurement Budget Line Items: USSF Vehicles (SFV000); General Information Tech - Space (GNRLIT)

 This program element includes all necessary expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver SSIO enterprise integration. The use of such program funds would be
 in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 1206392SF and 1206398SF. This requirement supports performance of a full financial audit as
 required by title 10 U.S.C. Chapter 9A, Sec 240-D.

