 The primary mission of SSIO is to orchestrate and integrate end-to-end capability delivery for warfighter operations across all Space Force Program Executive Officers
 (PEOs) and Portfolio Acquisition Executives (PAEs), Space Force Field Commands, Combatant Commands, and mission partners such as the Department of the Air
 Force Rapid Capabilities Office (AFRCO), the Missile Defense Agency (MDA), and the National Reconnaissance Office (NRO). SSIO is the only USSF office that looks
 throughout the fielded and programmed force to integrate kill chains across PEOs/PAEs and partners to deter, defeat, and dominate a dynamic red threat.

 In 2021, the Space Force established SSIO. In July 2024, the Assistant Secretary of the Air Force for Space Acquisition and Integration (ASAF)(SA&I) broadened
 SSIO's mission and designated SSIO as the organization responsible for integration across all Space Force PEO/PAE portfolios to include SSC, Space Development
 Agency (SDA), and the Space Rapid Capabilities Office (SpRCO). In April 2025, the ASAF(SA&I) appointed a Senior Advisor to the Service Acquisition Executive
 (SASAE), and, in response to a 2025 NDAA requirement, the Senior Advisor for Space Command, Control, and Integration (SASC2I). The SASAE is the USSF lead
 for System of Systems Engineering (SoSE) across the space acquisition enterprise and is responsible to drive engineering and assess all acquisition efforts under
 the authority of the ASAF(SA&I) portfolio and applicable mission partner organizations. This includes advising the Service Acquisition Executive (SAE) on matters of
 enforcement needed to enable and accelerate integrated enterprise capability delivery. The SASC2I is responsible for conducting oversight of all acquisition efforts
 within the authority of the ASAF(SA&I) with respect to developing, upgrading, deploying, and sustaining space command, control, and integration to meet the space
 command, control, and integration requirements of the combatant commands. SSIO executes the functions necessary to meet these responsibilities on behalf of the
 SASAE and SASC2I.

 SSIO advises the ASAF(SA&I) on strategy to inform PEO portfolios across all mission areas to meet warfighting needs. These efforts also provide systems engineering
 for the space component of the Command, Control, Communications, and Battle Management (C3BM) portfolio to deliver an integrated command and control
 architecture to support the joint fight. SSIO enterprise-level integration includes three lines of effort. The first is Enterprise Mission Integration and Analysis which
 supports a multitude of Space Force programs at all classification levels needed to close mission threads and kill chains and deliver war-winning capabilities. The

