Title: Enterprise Technical Governance and Requirements                                                                                          -       20.274         54.635
Description: Enterprise Technical Governance and Requirements establishes and enforces the space enterprise technical
baseline through a disciplined engineering and governance process, acting as a standards provider and integration adjudicator for
every space program. Governance of the technical baseline is executed through Space Enterprise Engineering and Configuration
Control Boards (SEERB & SECCB) where products from the Enterprise Mission Integration and Analysis Thrust in this Program,
such as authoritative technical standards, system-to-system interfaces, and end-to-end testing requirements for space and ground
architectures, are delivered and put into governance. Complementary standards from this Thrust for cyber, crypto, spectrum,

RDT&E Management Support

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
and a digital ecosystem enabled by Artificial Intelligence (AI) tools are also boarded, as are enterprise standards created in
collaboration with other mission partners. SSIO executes Service Acquisition Executive (SAE)-directed enterprise integration
assessments to ensure Program Executive Officers (PEOs)/Portfolio Acquisition Executives (PAEs) deliver fully integrated
and interoperable capabilities. These assessments are the SAE's primary tool for proactive enterprise risk management by
strategically assessing programs at acquisition milestones to verify compliance with the technical baseline and acquisitions best
practices. This creates a cohesive framework that is critical for integrating high-priority capabilities like the Command Control
Communications and Battle Management (C3BM) space component and rapidly onboarding commercial innovation and allied
systems. This process is deliberately dynamic, driven by a continuous cycle of requirements analysis informed by real-world
mission threads and evolving threats, ensuring the enterprise architecture remains tactically relevant and strategically aligned.
Funding this core function is a direct investment in programmatic risk reduction, preventing costly integration failures and ensuring
every capability is interoperable.

This effort also provides requirements and governance to support continuous Supply Chain Risk Management (SCRM) monitoring
to include critical materials and technologies, Space Industrial Base Working Group (SIBWG) membership and ability to steer
investment funding from across the space community towards USSF priorities, and an integrated Digital Ecosystem (interoperable
and networked cloud, digital and AI tools, data, machines, and users) in close partnership with other USSF programs, to
effectively execute the above activities.

FY 2026 Plans:
Execute the repeatable SoSE processes across SSIO enabling a configuration-managed Enterprise technical baseline that
standardizes configurations across the Space Force architecture. Prioritize and expand efforts for operational priorities such
as space superiority and C3BM. Document, standardize, and control interfaces between 9 critical systems. Analyze change
requests and their potential impact on mission execution. Transition technical baseline management to Model Based Systems
Engineering (MBSE) to more effectively assess the impact of change requests across the architecture. Align acquisition strategies
across USSF. Perform independent assessments, as directed by the SAE, to evaluate program maturity, assess integration
risks to the USSF architecture, and inform acquisition program decisions. Drive integration requirements with CSRO and PEO's
to mitigate enterprise risks that jeopardize mission integration required for executing the Joint Space Operations Plan. Address
emerging enterprise requirements with CSRO for disposition across programs. Establish integrated end-to-end mission capability
and mission thread test plans. Develop a comprehensive portfolio assessment and program integration scorecard that the SAE
will use to assess and enforce enterprise integration.
