Remarks

D. Acquisition Strategy
The SKA priority is to provide situational awareness hit assessment to the warfighter. The SKA efforts would closely align with the MDA Technology Development
acquisition life cycle phase. The acquisition strategy includes use of all available acquisition tools to include Military Interdepartmental Purchase Request, Support
Agreements, existing contracts, and new competitively awarded contracts to continue delivering hit and kill assessment capabilities. SKA leverages the extensive history
of experience of Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory (JHU/APL) performing kill assessment activities and conducting experiments associated with the
Aegis Ballistic Missile Defense program. JHU/APL developed the SKA experiment while the primary subcontractor was responsible for payload integration and hosting
accommodations using a firm fixed price contract. A direct contract has been awarded by MDA to the host integrator to improve communications and oversight. The
SKA experiment uses a commercial satellite program as the platform host for a Department of Defense payload, taking full advantage of a multi-billion dollar space and
ground system that already exists.




